tlet, going "naked as a sign," flogging, bundling, and scalping. All have implications for the study of gender, sexuality, masculinity, illness, the "body politic," spirituality, race, and slavery. The first book devoted solely to the history and theory of the body in early American cultural studies brings together authors representing diverse academic disciplines.Drawing on a wide range of archival sources—including itinerant ministers' journals, Revolutionary tracts and broadsides, advice manuals, and household inventories—they approach the theoretical analysis of the body in exciting new ways. A Centre of Wonders covers such varied topics as dance and movement among Native Americans; invading witch bodies in architecture and household spaces; rituals of baptism, conversion, and church discipline; eighteenth-century women's journaling; and the body as a rhetorical device in the language of diplomacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aHuman bodyxSymbolic aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aU.S. History. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh1 aBrown, Kathleen M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDillon, Elizabeth Maddock, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEden, Trudy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinch, Martha L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorge, Robert Blair St., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindman, Janet Moore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindman, Janet Moore, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMelish, Joanne Pope, econtributor.4ctb4http